Here is an explanation of the advanced JavaScript array methods 
— map(), filter(), reduce(), some(), every(), and forEach() — 

### 1. map()  
Creates a new array by applying a function to each element of the original array.

```js
const numbers = [1, 2, 3, 4];
const doubled = numbers.map(num => num * 2);
console.log(doubled); // [2, 4, 6, 8]
```
Each element is transformed by the function and stored in a new array.[1]

### 2. filter()  
Creates a new array containing only elements that pass a condition.

```js
const numbers = [1, 2, 3, 4];
const even = numbers.filter(num => num % 2 === 0);
console.log(even); // [2, 4]
```
In this example, only even numbers are included in the new array.[5][1]

### 3. reduce()  
Reduces an array to a single value by accumulating results from each element.

```js
const numbers = [1, 2, 3, 4];
const sum = numbers.reduce((acc, curr) => acc + curr, 0);
console.log(sum); // 10
```
Starts with an initial accumulator (0), adds each element to it, and returns the total.[1][5]

### 4. some()  
Checks if at least one element passes a condition, returns `true` or `false`.

```js
const numbers = [1, 2, 3, 4];
const hasEven = numbers.some(num => num % 2 === 0);
console.log(hasEven); // true
```
Returns true since the array has even numbers.[9]

### 5. every()  
Checks if all elements satisfy a condition, returns `true` or `false`.

```js
const numbers = [2, 4, 6];
const allEven = numbers.every(num => num % 2 === 0);
console.log(allEven); // true
```
Returns true only if all elements are even.[9]

### 6. forEach()  
Executes a function on each array element but returns nothing (undefined).

```js
const numbers = [1, 2, 3];
numbers.forEach(num => console.log(num * 2));
// Output: 2 4 6 (each printed on a new line)
```
Useful for side effects like logging or updating external variables. Does not create a new array.[5][9]

***

### Summary Table

| Method   | Description                      | Returns             | Mutates Original Array? |
|----------|---------------------------------|---------------------|------------------------|
| map()    | Transform every element          | New array           | No                     |
| filter() | Keep elements that pass test     | New array           | No                     |
| reduce() | Reduce to single cumulative value| Single value        | No                     |
| some()   | Test if any element passes test | Boolean             | No                     |
| every()  | Test if all elements pass test  | Boolean             | No                     |
| forEach()| Run function for each element    | undefined           | No                     |

